It seems to me that you and your two brothers and 
sister all have had successful careers. In which

28:32.415 --> 28:37.200
ways do you think that your parents are 
responsible for that? Well, when I got ready to go

28:38.952 --> 28:52.450
to A&M, my father told me, he said, I do not have the 
financial means to send you to A&M. See, I started

28:52.470 --> 28:58.498
in 1936, which was just coming out of the 
Depression. But he said, I'll tell you what I can

28:58.518 --> 29:00.420
do. He said, you can stay at home. I can board you. I 
can provide you with food and a place to live if you

29:04.837 --> 29:12.473
can find some way to commute back and forth. My 
grandfather had an old 1929 Chevrolet. He told me,

29:17.343 --> 29:22.273
he said, if you can get enough people to ride with 
you to help pay your expenses, I was sort of

29:22.962 --> 29:26.389
mechanically inclined. He said, I believe you 
could keep the old car up, and you can take that car

29:26.430 --> 29:37.714
and use it if you can commute back and forth and use 
it for your transportation. Well, I did. I got

29:39.312 --> 29:41.936
people that were interested in going back for it. 
Some of them were students. Some of them worked at

29:43.920 --> 29:44.461
A&M. Triple A was in B&M. That was part of the 
agriculture program. And I always had a load of

29:50.191 --> 29:53.216
people that wanted to go. And I'd gather them up in 
the morning after I milked seven cows, gather them

29:53.296 --> 29:59.247
up, head to A&M. go to school all day, and I worked. I 
worked for the landscape department on the

30:02.177 --> 30:05.380
grounds. Doing anything I had to do. I picked 
mealybugs off the chrysanthemums, I dug in the

30:08.543 --> 30:19.612
flowerbeds, I hauled compost out of the Calvary 
stables. You know, whatever there was to do, I was

30:19.632 --> 30:25.358
ready, because I wanted to go to school. And I got 30 
cents an hour. And I was allowed to work. Which was

30:32.036 --> 30:33.998
above minimum wage actually. I think it was. It 
was. The first minimum wage went in in 37 and that

30:36.241 --> 30:42.308
was only 25 cents an hour. Well we were paid. Or 38, 
1938. Well we were getting 30 at that time and I was

30:44.831 --> 30:49.816
allowed to work 40 hours a month. A day student 
could work 40 hours a month. That's right. And that

30:54.402 --> 30:57.145
gave me $12 a month. And that made the difference in 
homeschool. Had I not gotten that $12 a month, I

31:00.955 --> 31:05.400
couldn't have made it. Because that brought my 
little books and paper and pencils and whatnot.

